s, are human and historical, writes Steinberg. Political constitutions, as a form of beginning, imply the eventuality of their own renewals and their own reconstitutions. Motivated in part by recent reactionary insurgencies in the US, Europe, and Israel, this astute work of intellectual history posits the critique of myths of origin as a key principle of democratic government, affect, and citizenship, of their endurance as well as their fragility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aExodus, The. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aAbraham Lincoln.  aDemocracy.  aExile.  aFreud.  aHannah Arendt.  aIsrael.  aMoses.  aRace.  aReconstitutions.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363230140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632301/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles